---
import Layout from "../../components/Layout.astro";
import Header from "../../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import ArticleCard from "../../components/ArticleCard.astro";
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";

const articles = await getCollection("articles");
const sorted = articles.sort(
  (a, b) => new Date(b.data.pubDate).getTime() - new Date(a.data.pubDate).getTime()
);
---

<Layout
  title="Insights — Autonomy Bridge"
  description="Warehouse robotics economics, automation deployment analysis, and failure mode research. Structured analysis for operators, investors, and vendors evaluating industrial automation decisions."
  canonicalPath="/insights"
>
  <Header />

  <main class="container site-main">
    <h1>Insights</h1>
    <p class="subhead reading-column">
      Warehouse automation economics, deployment risk, and operational analysis
      for operators, investors, and vendors making high-stakes robotics decisions.
    </p>

    <section class="section reading-column">
      <h2>Warehouse Robotics Market Structure</h2>
      <p>
        Warehouse automation is a capital-intensive market driven by utilization
        economics, not robot specifications. Understanding how deployments are
        structured, priced, and evaluated is a prerequisite for any high-stakes
        automation decision.
      </p>
      <h3>Deployment Economics</h3>
      <p>
        AMR and goods-to-person systems convert variable labour into fixed
        infrastructure cost. Payback depends on whether real order volume
        sustains the utilization required to recover capital across the system
        life — not on robot speed or throughput capability.
      </p>
      <h3>Vendor Architecture Landscape</h3>
      <p>
        The AMR vendor market is fragmented across autonomous mobile robots,
        goods-to-person systems, and hybrid architectures. Vendor economics,
        pricing models, and deployment conditions vary significantly and are
        rarely comparable using vendor-supplied ROI tools.
      </p>
      <h3>Failure Modes</h3>
      <p>
        Most warehouse automation failures are economic rather than technical:
        utilization collapse, bottleneck migration, integration instability, and
        retrofit layout constraints. Understanding these failure modes is
        essential before committing capital.
      </p>
      <h3>Decision-Grade Analysis</h3>
      <p>
        Operator decisions require facility-specific economic modelling, not
        market benchmarks. The articles below provide the analytical foundations
        for evaluating automation investments on their own terms.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="content-grid">
      {sorted.map((article) => (
        <ArticleCard
          title={article.data.title}
          description={article.data.description}
          slug={article.slug}
          cluster={article.data.cluster}
          pubDate={article.data.pubDate}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
